WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.500
<v Sarah (Interviewer)>Hello Alex! Welcome to the technical interview sync. How are you doing today?</v>

00:00:05.200 --> 00:00:08.800
<v Alex (Candidate)>Hi Sarah! I am doing great, thank you. Very excited to discuss the role and the platform.</v>

00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:15.000
<v Sarah (Interviewer)>Awesome. To start, could you give a quick overview of your experience building real-time integrations, particularly with Microsoft Graph?</v>

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:24.500
<v Alex (Candidate)>Sure! In my previous project, we built a similar flow where we needed to block calendars and sync Teams meeting recordings and transcripts.</v>

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:32.500
<v Alex (Candidate)>We implemented an Azure Entra ID app registration using Application Permissions, specifically the client credentials flow for headless token fetching.</v>

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:41.000
<v Sarah (Interviewer)>That is exactly what we are designing! How did you handle the webhook notification for transcript completion without overloading Microsoft servers?</v>

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:48.500
<v Alex (Candidate)>We subscribed to communications/onlineMeetings/getAllTranscripts using Graph change notifications. When the call ended, Microsoft POSTed the ID.</v>

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:54.800
<v Alex (Candidate)>Our backend received the webhook, validated the life-cycle token, and fetched the raw VTT content and MP4 video in the background.</v>

00:00:55.500 --> 00:01:00.200
<v Sarah (Interviewer)>Fantastic. Let's dig deeper. How did you sync the transcript cues to the HTML5 video player on the frontend UI?</v>

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:07.500
<v Alex (Candidate)>We parsed the WebVTT file into time-indexed nodes. When the user clicked a line, we seeked the player. We also used timeupdate events to scroll and highlight text.</v>

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:12.000
<v Sarah (Interviewer)>Impressive work. Well, that covers our core architectural needs. Let's move on to coding!</v>
